{
  "To demonstrate it, let's say we were building a carousel like experience whose content was different Pokémon from the <a href=\"https://pokeapi.co/\" metastring=\"\">PokéAPI</a>.": "",
  "We know based on <button aria-controls=\"radix-:rlr:\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-haspopup=\"dialog\" class=\"Popover_children__8p5Di\" data-state=\"closed\" type=\"button\"><span>Rule #0</span> <svg class=\"fill-brand-purple dark:fill-brand-yellow w-2 h-2 b-2 mx-0.5 mb-4\" enable-background=\"new 0 0 455 455\" version=\"1.1\" viewbox=\"0 0 455 455\" x=\"0\" xml:space=\"preserve\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" y=\"0\"><path d=\"M347.49 227L454.5 165.212 394.508 61.288 287.5 123.077 287.5 0 167.5 0 167.5 123.077 60.492 61.288 0.499 165.212 107.51 227 0.5 288.788 60.492 392.712 167.5 330.923 167.5 455 287.5 455 287.5 330.923 394.508 392.712 454.501 288.788z\"></path></svg></button> that we need to keep our network request out of React's rendering flow. Now we just need to decide <strong metastring=\"\">where</strong> we put it, either in an event handler or in <code>useEffect</code>.": "",
  "This becomes obvious when we break it down further. What exactly does <em metastring=\"\">\"whenever the user interacts with our carousel\"</em> actually mean? When they click a button? What about navigating with their keyboard? What if we wanted our carousel to change Pokemon automatically every few seconds? What about on the initial render when there's no user interaction but we still need to fetch the first Pokémon?": "",
  "The take away here is there's no single event that should trigger our network request. Instead, what we're really wanting to do is <em metastring=\"\">synchronize</em> our component with the result of calling the Pokémon API – the perfect use case for <code>useEffect</code>.": "",
  "Before we worry the async bits, let's build out the basic logic for our carousel first. Again, the entire premise of this app is to synchronize our component with the result of calling the Pokémon API. To do that, we'll need some state. Specifically, we'll add an <code>id</code> state to keep track of the <code>id</code> of the Pokémon we're currently viewing and a <code>pokemon</code> state to keep track of the actual Pokémon data. Our <code>id</code> state will default to <code>1</code> since that's the <code>id</code> of the first Pokémon, Bulbasaur.": "",
  "We'll then encapsulate the async logic for fetching a Pokémon into a function called <code>fetchPokemon</code>. Now, whenever we invoke <code>fetchPokemon</code> passing it an <code>id</code> of the Pokémon we want to fetch, we'll get back an object with an <code>error</code> if there was one or a <code>response</code> of the Pokémon data if there wasn't.": "",
  "Now the fun part. We want to synchronize our local <code>pokemon</code> state with the PokéAPI according to our local <code>id</code> state. That's a fancy way of saying whenever our local <code>id</code> state changes, we want to invoke <code>fetchPokemon</code> passing it the new <code>id</code>. We'll do that by calling <code>fetchPokemon</code> inside of <code>useEffect</code> and then updating our <code>pokemon</code> state with the result.": "",
  "First, notice that our dependency array only includes one element, <code>id</code>. Again, this <strong metastring=\"\">isn't</strong> telling React to re-run the effect when <code>id</code> changes (though, that's what happens). Instead, we're giving React an array of all of the dependencies our effect needs to re-synchronize with the outside system. As a <em metastring=\"\">byproduct</em> of that, whenever React sees that <code>id</code> has changed between renders, it will re-run the effect.": "",
  "Second, you may be wondering why we declared a new <code>handleFetchPokemon</code> function inside of our event. This is purely aesthetic and was done so that we could use <code>async</code>/<code>await</code> inside of <code>useEffect</code>.": "",
  "First, we'll need to add two new pieces of state to our component, <code>loading</code> and <code>error</code>. Because <code>fetchPokemon</code> is invoked as a result of rendering, including the initial render, we'll initialize <code>loading</code> to <code>true</code> (and <code>error</code> to <code>null</code>).": "",
  "Now we need our effect to manage our new <code>loading</code> and <code>error</code> states. Thankfully our <code>fetchPokemon</code> function makes this easy since it's so explicit if there's an error.": "",
  "What we'll do is whenever our effects runs, reset <code>loading</code> and <code>error</code> back to their default values before we make the network request. Then, once we get back a response, if there's an error, we'll update <code>error</code>, and if not, we'll update <code>pokemon</code> before setting <code>loading</code> to <code>false</code>.": "",
  "Don't get freaked out over the multiple, separate invocations of our updater functions (<code>setError</code>, <code>setPokemon</code>, <code>setLoading</code>). Remember, React \"batches\" those together intelligently so there's no wasted renders.": "",
  "You could argue at this point the hardest parts are behind us. It appears we've successfully abstracted the arduous async side effect bits into <code>useEffect</code>, and are now synchronizing our component with the PokéAPI.": "",
  "Notice the simplicity of our app now. Because we've told <code>useEffect</code> to synchronize our local <code>pokemon</code> state with the PokéAPI according to <code>id</code>, we've taken what has historically been the most complex part of building a web app, an asynchronous side effect, and made it an implementation detail behind simply updating <code>id</code> via our <code>handlePrevious</code> and <code>handleNext</code> functions.": "",
  "Now, unfortunately, we're not <em metastring=\"\">quite</em> done yet. As is, our code contains the <em metastring=\"\">worst</em> kind of bug – one that is both inconspicuous and deceptively wasteful. Can you spot it?": "",
  "Whenever we call <code>fetchPokemon</code>, because it's an asynchronous request, we have no idea how long that request will take to resolve. It's completely possible that, while we're in the process of waiting for a response, our Carousel updates <code>id</code>, which causes a re-render, which causes our effect to run again with a different <code>id</code>.": "",
  "In this scenario, we now have two requests in flight, both with different <code>id</code>s. Worse, we have no way of knowing which one will resolve first. In both scenarios, we're calling <code>setPokemon</code> when the request resolves. That means, because we don't know in which order they'll resolve, <code>pokemon</code>, and therefor our UI, will eventually be <em metastring=\"\">whatever request was resolved last</em>. To make it worse, you'll also get a flash of the Pokémon that resolves first, before the second one does.": "",
  "Really what we want to do is to tell React to ignore any responses that come from requests that were made in effects that are no longer relevant. In order to do that, of course, we need a way to know if an effect is the latest one. If not, then we should ignore the response and <strong metastring=\"\">not</strong> <code>setPokemon</code> inside of it.": "",
  "Thankfully, React makes this pretty easy with the last remaining feature of <code>useEffect</code> you haven't seen yet: the \"cleanup\" function.": "",
  "We can see this in action by adding a cleanup function to our effect that logs the <code>id</code> that the effect is associated with.": "",
  "Notice that the cleanup function is only called for <code>id</code>s that are no longer relevant. This makes sense because the cleanup function for the most recent effect won't be called until either <em metastring=\"\">another</em> effect runs (making it stale) or the component has been removed from the DOM (irrelevant in this scenario).": "",
  "We can use this knowledge along with the <span class=\"sparkle_wrapper__cL2jQ\"><span class=\"sparkle_sparkle_wrapper__Izdcu\" style=\"top:85%;left:35%\"><svg class=\"sparkle_sparkle_svg__WdZ3Y\" fill=\"none\" height=\"18\" viewbox=\"0 0 68 68\" width=\"18\"><path d=\"M 48 5 L 51 27 L 74 30 L 51 33 L 48 56 L 44 33 L 23 30 L 44 27 Z\" fill=\"var(--yellow)\"></path></svg></span><span class=\"sparkle_sparkle_wrapper__Izdcu\" style=\"top:89%;left:76%\"><svg class=\"sparkle_sparkle_svg__WdZ3Y\" fill=\"none\" height=\"17\" viewbox=\"0 0 68 68\" width=\"17\"><path d=\"M 48 5 L 51 27 L 74 30 L 51 33 L 48 56 L 44 33 L 23 30 L 44 27 Z\" fill=\"var(--yellow)\"></path></svg></span><span class=\"sparkle_sparkle_wrapper__Izdcu\" style=\"top:73%;left:46%\"><svg class=\"sparkle_sparkle_svg__WdZ3Y\" fill=\"none\" height=\"13\" viewbox=\"0 0 68 68\" width=\"13\"><path d=\"M 48 5 L 51 27 L 74 30 L 51 33 L 48 56 L 44 33 L 23 30 L 44 27 Z\" fill=\"var(--yellow)\"></path></svg></span><strong class=\"sparkle_child_wrapper__bem0y\">Power of JavaScript™</strong></span> to fix our problem.": "",
  "Whenever the effect runs, let's make a variable called <code>ignore</code> and set it to <code>false</code>. Then, whenever the cleanup function runs (which we know will only happen when the effect is stale), we'll set <code>ignore</code> to <code>true</code>.": "",
  "Then, all we have to do before we call <code>setPokemon</code> or <code>setError</code>, is check to see if <code>ignore</code> is <code>true</code>. If it is, then we'll do nothing.": "",
  "Now, regardless of how many times <code>id</code> changes, we'll ignore every response that isn't in the most recent effect. This not only makes our app more performant, but it also improves the UX since React will now only re-render with the latest Pokémon.": "",
  "You can use the document's <code>visibilitychange</code> event to detect when the page is no longer visible.": "",
  "First, let's add some state to track the number of times the employee has tabbed away. We'll call this <code>count</code> and we'll also add some UI for the user to see their count.": "",
  "Now the tricky part. We need to listen for the <code>visibilitychange</code> event and update our <code>count</code> state accordingly. Since we're synchronizing the document's visibility status with our component, we'll use <code>useEffect</code>.": "",
  "First let's add our event listener. Remember, whenever you add an event listener, you also need to remove it when the component is removed from the DOM or you'll have a memory leak. <code>useEffect</code>'s cleanup function makes this simple.": "",
  "Now all we need to do is update our <code>handleChange</code> function to increment our <code>count</code> state whenever the document is no longer visible. Your first intuition might be to do something like this – where we add <code>count</code> to our dependency array and then increment it by <code>1</code> inside of <code>handleChange</code>.": "",
  "Whenever the document's <code>visibilityState</code> is no longer visible, we increment <code>count</code> by one. Simple, right? Yes, but actually no. In fact, even though our app appears to be working fine, there's a major problem. Can you spot it?": "",
  "Via our dependency array, we've told React that our effect depends on our <code>count</code> state (which is true). That means, whenever <code>count</code> changes, React will re-render and then, once it's done, re-invoke our effect.": "",
  "We're in a weird spot. We only want React to add our event listener once, on the initial mount, but we need to include <code>count</code> in the dependency array because we're using it inside of the effect to calculate the new <code>count</code> state.": "",
  "What's interesting about this example compared to our other examples is, even though we're using <code>count</code> in the effect, we're not using it as a way to synchronize our component with some external system – so we don't actually need React re-run the effect when it changes.": "",
  "Thankfully, React has a solution for these types of scenarios and it's probably not what you'd expect. In fact, it has nothing to do with <code>useEffect</code> at all. Instead, it has to do with <em metastring=\"\">how</em> we're updating our <code>count</code> state.": "",
  "In both of these examples, we're telling React to increment <code>count</code> by <code>1</code>. However, the difference is in how we're getting access to the current state of <code>count</code> before we increment it. In the first example, we're relying on a closure – and therefore we have to specify <code>count</code> inside of the dependency array. In the second, we're not, since React will pass us the current state of <code>count</code> as an argument and therefore, we don't need to include it in the dependency array.": "",
  "With this knowledge, we can now update our example to remove <code>count</code> from the dependency array which prevents React from re-running our effect every time it changes.": "",
  "First is how <code>StrictMode</code> affects <code>useEffect</code>. If you're not familiar, <code>StrictMode</code> is a component that comes with React that allows you to stress test your application in <strong metastring=\"\">development</strong>.": "",
  "When you have <code>StrictMode</code> \"enabled\" (which is the default for most React apps), React will re-render an <strong metastring=\"\">extra</strong> time, re-run effects an <strong metastring=\"\">extra</strong> time, and check for deprecated APIs.": "",
  "Why is this helpful? You can think of <code>StrictMode</code> as a stress test of our 3 rules. If render is not pure or you're incorrectly managing side effects, <code>StrictMode</code> will (aggressively) uncover that.": "",
  "It's controversial, but the whole goal of <code>StrictMode</code> is to make it more obvious that you're doing something wrong – which I think is a reasonable goal. If you stick to the rules we've established, <code>StrictMode</code> will be mostly irrelevant for you.": "",
  "For more information on it, check out the <a href=\"https://react.dev/reference/react/StrictMode\" metastring=\"\">official documentation</a>.": "",
  "Throughout our discussion on effects, you may have been wondering the distinction between what needs to be included in <code>useEffect</code>'s dependency array and what doesn't. For example, why doesn't <code>localStorage</code>, <code>Number</code>, or <code>setIndex</code> need to be included in our <code>Greeting</code> effect?": "",
  "The reason is because they're not <strong metastring=\"\">reactive</strong> values. Defined, a reactive value is any value that can change between re-renders. Props, state, or any variables defined inside of a component are all reactive values – and therefore, always need to be included in the dependency array if they're used in the effect.": "",
  "In our example, <code>localStorage</code> and <code>Number</code> are always going to reference the same spot in memory and React guarantees that the <code>setIndex</code> updater function will also always be consistent across renders, meaning all of these are <strong metastring=\"\">non</strong> reactive values.": "",
  "This makes sense if you think about it. The whole goal of <code>useEffect</code> is to synchronize your component with some outside system. Non reactive values are irrelevant to <code>useEffect</code> because they're never used in the synchronization process.": ""
}